ix]]\n|10||0||30.7||.370||.364||.706||3.1||1.7||1.4||0.3||8.2\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[1996 NBA Playoffs|1996]]\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[1995\u201396 Cleveland Cavaliers season|Cleveland]]\n|3||0||30.3||.444||'''.435'''||.889||4.0||3.0||1.3||0.7||16.7\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[1997 NBA Playoffs|1997]]\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[1996\u201397 Miami Heat season|Miami]]\n|17||2||29.2||.393||.338||.679||4.2||2.5||1.2||0.2||8.0\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[1998 NBA Playoffs|1998]]\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[1997\u201398 Miami Heat season|Miami]]\n|2||2||31.0||.375||.333||.500||2.5||2.5||2.0||0.5||4.5\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[1999 NBA Playoffs|1999]]\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[1998\u201399 Miami Heat season|Miami]]\n|5||5||30.4||.192||.227||.714||5.8||1.2||1.0||0.4||4.0\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2000 NBA Playoffs|2000]]\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[1999\u20132000 Miami Heat season|Miami]]\n|10||10||37.2||.423||.400||.714||'''7.0'''||3.2||'''2.1'''||0.1||9.0\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2001 NBA Playoffs|2001]]\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|[[2000\u201301 Miami Heat season|Miami]]\n|3||0||23.7||.313||.286||.500||3.3||1.7||1.0||0.0||5.3\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" colspan=\"2\"| Career\n| 123 || 53 || 34.5 || .416 || .353 || .753 || 5.0 || 2.5 || 1.3 || 0.4 || 11.7\n{{S-end\n}}\n\n==Post-NBA career==\nMajerle was inducted into the [[Phoenix Suns Ring of Honor]] on March 9, 2003.<ref name=\"NBA coachfile\">[http://www.nba.com/coachfile/dan_majerle/ NBA.com Dan Majerle<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> In 2006, he was inducted into the [[Michigan Sports Hall of Fame]] and into the [[Arizona Sports Hall of Fame]] in 2017.  In 2003, Majerle made his broadcasting debut covering the [[2003 NBA Playoffs]] for [[NBA on TNT|TNT]] and later became an analyst for [[NBA on ESPN|ESPN]]. During the [[2005 NBA All-Star Weekend|2005 All-Star Weekend]], he was a member of the Phoenix team that won the [[NBA All-Star Weekend Shooting Stars Competition|Shooting Stars Competition]].<ref>{{cite web|title=NBA All-Star Shooting Stars Winners|date=August 24, 2017|website=NBA.com|url=http://www.nba.com/history/all-star/shooting-stars#/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180224155543/http://www.nba.com/history/all-star/shooting-stars|archivedate=February 24, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Coaching==\n\n===Phoenix Suns===\nMajerle was the associate head coach for the Phoenix Suns from 2008\u20132013.\n\n===Grand Canyon University===\nOn March 15, 2013, it was announced that Majerle would coach for [[Grand Canyon University]] in their first season as a Division I team.<ref>{{cite web|title=DAN MAJERLE NAMED GCU MEN'S BASKETBALL COACH|url=http://www.gcu.edu/News/News-2013/Dan-Majerle-Named-GCU-Mens-Basketball-Coach.php|publisher=gcu.edu|accessdate=May 30, 2014|date=March 18, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn December 23, 2015, Majerle led [[Grand Canyon Antelopes men's basketball|Grand Canyon]] to their first tournament victory as a Division 1 team when they won the [[2015 Global Sports Classic]] championship.<ref>[http://www.gculopes.com/news/2015/12/23/MBB_1223150600.aspx Grand Canyon University - GCU takes Global Sports Classic title with win over Marshall<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nHe was fired on March 17, 2020 after his first losing season.\n\n==Personal life==\nMajerle owns five sports grill restaurants called \"Majerle's\".<ref>[http://www.majerles.com/ Majerle\\'s Sports Grill | Downtown Phoenix, Chandler, Goodyear, Scottsdale, Arizona<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nDan has four kids with Tina Majerle:\nMadison, McKenzie, Mia, and, Max, who also plays basketball\n\n==Head coaching record==\n{{CBB Yearly Record Start | type = | conference = | postseason = | poll = }}\n{{CBB Yearly Record Subhead\n | name      = [[Grand Canyon Antelopes men's basketball|Grand Canyon Antelopes]]\n | conference= [[Western Athletic Conference]]\n | startyear = 2013\n 